# Java Conventions

## Language & Platform
- Java 21 with JPMS (Java Platform Module System)
- JavaFX 23.0.1 for UI
- Gradle 9.0 multi-module build
- Each module has a `module-info.java` declaring exports, opens, requires, and provides

## Constants
- All string literals, magic numbers, and configuration values go in `SpeleoDBConstants`
- Organized into nested final classes: `API`, `HEADERS`, `HTTP_STATUS`, `NETWORK`, `MESSAGES`, `STYLES`, `DIMENSIONS`, `TIMINGS`, `JSON_FIELDS`, etc.
- Reference via static import or qualified name: `MESSAGES.AUTH_FAILED_STATUS`

## Logging
- Use `SpeleoDBLogger.getInstance()` exclusively -- never `System.out.println` or `System.err.println` in production code
- Log levels: `debug()` (file only), `info()` (file + UI), `warn()` (file + UI), `error()` (file + UI)
- Logger is a singleton with file rotation and UI console integration

## Naming
- Fields and locals: camelCase (`sdbInstance`, `httpClient`, `tmlFilepath`)
- Never use snake_case for Java identifiers
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` inside `SpeleoDBConstants` nested classes

## Error Handling
- Never use `catch (Exception ignored) {}` silently -- at minimum log with `logger.debug()`
- Use `IllegalStateException` for precondition failures (e.g., not authenticated)
- Use `IllegalArgumentException` for invalid input
- Custom exceptions: `NotModifiedException` for HTTP 304

## JSON
- Use `jakarta.json` API (`Json.createReader`, `Json.createObjectBuilder`)
- Never parse JSON with manual `indexOf`/`substring`
- Use `JSON_FIELDS.*` constants for field names

## HTTP
- Use `java.net.http.HttpClient` with proper timeouts from `NETWORK.*` constants
- `createHttpClientForInstance(String)` selects HTTP version based on protocol
- All requests must include `timeout()` from `NETWORK.REQUEST_TIMEOUT_SECONDS`

## Singletons
- `SpeleoDBController`: eagerly initialized `private static final` instance
- `SpeleoDBLogger`: lazy singleton with double-checked locking
- Both use `CountDownLatch` or locks for thread safety
